<div class="section" style="background-color: var(--light-color)">
  <div class="container">
    <h2 class="section-title">Menstrual Cycle Basics</h2>

    <div class="row">
      <div class="col-lg-6">
        <div class="card h-100">
          <div class="card-body">
            <h4 class="card-title">What is the Menstrual Cycle?</h4>
            <p>
              The menstrual cycle is a series of natural changes in hormone
              production and the structures of the uterus and ovaries that make
              pregnancy possible. The average cycle length is 28 days, but it
              can range from 21 to 35 days.
            </p>
            <p>
              The cycle is regulated by hormones from the brain
              (follicle-stimulating hormone and luteinizing hormone) and the
              ovaries (estrogen and progesterone).
            </p>
            <p>Understanding your menstrual cycle helps you:</p>
            <ul>
              <li>Predict when your period will occur</li>
              <li>Identify your fertile window if trying to conceive</li>
              <li>Recognize when something might be abnormal</li>
              <li>Better understand your body's patterns and changes</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="col-lg-6">
        <div class="card h-100">
          <div class="card-body">
            <h4 class="card-title">The Four Phases</h4>
            <ol>
              <li>
                <strong>Menstrual Phase (Days 1-5):</strong>
                <ul>
                  <li>
                    The uterine lining sheds through the vagina as a period
                  </li>
                  <li>Day 1 of bleeding is considered day 1 of the cycle</li>
                  <li>Typically lasts 3-7 days</li>
                </ul>
              </li>
              <li>
                <strong>Follicular Phase (Days 1-13):</strong>
                <ul>
                  <li>Overlaps with the menstrual phase</li>
                  <li>Follicles (egg sacs) in the ovaries begin to mature</li>
                  <li>Estrogen levels rise</li>
                  <li>The uterine lining starts to thicken</li>
                </ul>
              </li>
              <li>
                <strong>Ovulation (Day 14, approximately):</strong>
                <ul>
                  <li>A mature egg is released from an ovary</li>
                  <li>The egg travels down the fallopian tube</li>
                  <li>Can be accompanied by mild pain or spotting</li>
                  <li>This is the most fertile time</li>
                </ul>
              </li>
              <li>
                <strong>Luteal Phase (Days 15-28):</strong>
                <ul>
                  <li>The ruptured follicle forms the corpus luteum</li>
                  <li>Progesterone levels rise</li>
                  <li>The uterine lining continues to thicken</li>
                  <li>
                    If pregnancy doesn't occur, hormone levels drop and the
                    cycle begins again
                  </li>
                </ul>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="section">
  <div class="container">
    <h2 class="section-title">Sexual Health Topics</h2>

    <div class="row">
      <div class="col-md-6 col-lg-4 mb-4">
        <div class="info-card h-100">
          <div class="info-card-content">
            <h4>Consent and Communication</h4>
            <p>
              Healthy sexual relationships are built on clear consent and open
              communication.
            </p>
            <h5 class="mt-3">Key principles of consent:</h5>
            <ul>
              <li>
                Freely given - without pressure, manipulation, or under the
                influence of substances
              </li>
              <li>Reversible - can be withdrawn at any time</li>
              <li>Informed - all parties understand what's involved</li>
              <li>Enthusiastic - all parties genuinely want to participate</li>
              <li>
                Specific - saying yes to one activity doesn't mean yes to others
              </li>
            </ul>
            <p>
              Communication about boundaries, desires, and protection is
              essential for a satisfying and safe sexual experience.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="col-md-6 col-lg-4 mb-4">
        <div class="info-card h-100">
          <div class="info-card-content">
            <h4>Sexually Transmitted Infections (STIs)</h4>
            <p>
              STIs are infections that can be transmitted through sexual
              contact. Common STIs include:
            </p>
            <ul>
              <li>Chlamydia</li>
              <li>Gonorrhea</li>
              <li>Herpes</li>
              <li>Human Papillomavirus (HPV)</li>
              <li>Syphilis</li>
              <li>HIV</li>
              <li>Trichomoniasis</li>
            </ul>
            <h5 class="mt-3">Prevention:</h5>
            <ul>
              <li>
                Use barriers (condoms, dental dams) during sexual activity
              </li>
              <li>Get vaccinated against HPV and hepatitis B</li>
              <li>Get regular STI testing</li>
              <li>Communicate with partners about sexual health</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="col-md-6 col-lg-4 mb-4">
        <div class="info-card h-100">
          <div class="info-card-content">
            <h4>Pleasure and Sexual Well-being</h4>
            <p>
              Sexual pleasure is an important aspect of overall well-being.
              Understanding your body and what brings you pleasure is healthy
              and normal.
            </p>
            <h5 class="mt-3">Components of sexual well-being:</h5>
            <ul>
              <li>Physical pleasure and satisfaction</li>
              <li>Emotional connection and intimacy</li>
              <li>Body confidence and self-acceptance</li>
              <li>Freedom from shame or anxiety</li>
              <li>Ability to communicate needs and boundaries</li>
            </ul>
            <p>
              If you experience pain, discomfort, or concerns related to sexual
              function, consult with a healthcare provider. Many sexual
              difficulties can be addressed with proper care.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="section" style="background-color: var(--light-color)">
  <div class="container">
    <h2 class="section-title">Common Reproductive Health Concerns</h2>

    <div class="row">
      <div class="col-md-6 mb-4">
        <div class="card h-100">
          <div class="card-body">
            <h4 class="card-title">Irregular Periods</h4>
            <p>
              Menstrual cycles that are consistently shorter than 21 days or
              longer than 35 days, or that vary significantly from month to
              month.
            </p>
            <h5>Possible causes:</h5>
            <ul>
              <li>Hormonal imbalances</li>
              <li>Polycystic ovary syndrome (PCOS)</li>
              <li>Thyroid disorders</li>
              <li>Extreme weight loss or gain</li>
              <li>Excessive exercise</li>
              <li>Stress</li>
              <li>Perimenopause</li>
              <li>Certain medications</li>
            </ul>
            <p>
              When to see a doctor: If your periods are consistently irregular,
              very painful, or if you miss three or more periods in a row (and
              aren't pregnant).
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="col-md-6 mb-4">
        <div class="card h-100">
          <div class="card-body">
            <h4 class="card-title">Pelvic Pain</h4>
            <p>
              Pain in the lower abdomen that may be sharp, cramping,
              intermittent, or constant.
            </p>
            <h5>Possible causes:</h5>
            <ul>
              <li>Menstrual cramps</li>
              <li>Ovulation pain</li>
              <li>Endometriosis</li>
              <li>Pelvic inflammatory disease (PID)</li>
              <li>Fibroids</li>
              <li>Ovarian cysts</li>
              <li>Urinary tract infection</li>
              <li>Gastrointestinal issues</li>
            </ul>
            <p>
              When to see a doctor: If pain is severe, persistent, or
              accompanied by fever, vomiting, abnormal vaginal discharge, or if
              it disrupts daily activities.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="col-md-6 mb-4">
        <div class="card h-100">
          <div class="card-body">
            <h4 class="card-title">Vaginal Infections</h4>
            <p>
              Infections that cause changes in vaginal discharge, odor, itching,
              or discomfort.
            </p>
            <h5>Common types:</h5>
            <ul>
              <li>
                <strong>Bacterial Vaginosis (BV):</strong> Overgrowth of certain
                bacteria, causing fishy odor and thin, gray discharge
              </li>
              <li>
                <strong>Yeast Infections:</strong> Fungal infection causing
                thick, white discharge and intense itching
              </li>
              <li>
                <strong>Trichomoniasis:</strong> Sexually transmitted infection
                causing greenish-yellow discharge, itching, and burning
              </li>
            </ul>
            <p>
              When to see a doctor: If you have abnormal discharge, especially
              with strong odor, itching, burning, or pain during urination or
              intercourse.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="col-md-6 mb-4">
        <div class="card h-100">
          <div class="card-body">
            <h4 class="card-title">Fertility Concerns</h4>
            <p>
              Difficulty conceiving after 12 months of regular, unprotected
              intercourse (or 6 months if woman is over 35).
            </p>
            <h5>Possible factors:</h5>
            <ul>
              <li>
                Age (female fertility declines after 30, more significantly
                after 35)
              </li>
              <li>Irregular ovulation</li>
              <li>Blocked fallopian tubes</li>
              <li>Endometriosis</li>
              <li>Uterine or cervical conditions</li>
              <li>Male factors (low sperm count or motility)</li>
              <li>Lifestyle factors (smoking, alcohol, weight)</li>
            </ul>
            <p>
              When to see a doctor: If you've been trying to conceive for 12
              months (or 6 months if over 35) without success, or if you have
              known factors that might affect fertility.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="section">
